SIMPLE: girdle
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Girdle
<hw>Gir"dle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A griddle.</def>
<mark>[Scot. & Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Girdle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Girdle
<hw>Gir"dle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>gurdel</ets>,
<ets>girdel</ets>, AS. <ets>gyrdel</ets>, fr. <ets>gyrdan</ets>; akin to
D. <ets>gordel</ets>, G. <ets>g⟦uum⟧rtel</ets>, Icel.
<ets>gyr<?/ill</ets>. See <er>Gird</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, to encircle,
and cf. <er>Girth</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>That which girds, encircles, or incloses; a
circumference; a belt; esp., a belt, sash, or article of dress
encircling the body usually at the waist; a cestus.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> Within the <qex>girdle</qex> of these walls.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their breasts girded with golden <qex>girdles</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Rev. xv. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The zodiac; also, the equator.</def>
<mark>[Poetic]</mark> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From the world's <qex>girdle</qex> to the frozen pole.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That gems the starry <qex>girdle</qex> of the year.</q>
<rj><qau>Campbell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Jewelry)</fld> <def>The line ofgreatest
circumference of a brilliant-cut diamond, at which it is grasped by the
setting. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Brilliant</er>.</def>
<rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A thin bed or stratum of
stone.</def> <rj><au>Raymond.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The clitellus of an
earthworm.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Girdle bone</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>the
sphenethmoid. See under <er>Sphenethmoid</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Girdle
wheel</b></col>, <cd>a spinning wheel.</cd> -- <col><b>Sea
girdle</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a ctenophore. See <cref>Venus's
girdle</cref>, under <er>Venus</er>.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>Shoulder</b></col>, <col><b>Pectoral</b></col>, ⟦and⟧
<col><b>Pelvic</b></col>, <col><b>girdle</b></col></mcol>.
<fld>(Anat.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Pectoral</er>, and
<er>Pelvic</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>To have under the girdle</b></col>,
<cd>to have bound to one, that is, in subjection.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Girdle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Girdle
<hw>Gir"dle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Girdled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Girdling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To bind
with a belt or sash; to gird.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To inclose; to environ; to shut in.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those sleeping stones,⟦br⟧
That as a waist doth <qex>girdle</qex> you about.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make a cut or gnaw a groove around (a tree, etc.)
through the bark and alburnum, thus killing it.</def> <mark>[U.
S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Girdler</ent>⟦br⟧
